The paper deals with the problem of causal discovery from observational data, which is a topic that is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. The methods and benchmarks presented in the paper are related to machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI), as they involve the use of statistical models and algorithms to infer causal relationships. The paper also discusses information theory (cs.IT) and statistical inference (cs.ST) concepts that are relevant to causal discovery. Finally, the benchmarks cover a wide range of domains, including meteorology, biology, medicine, engineering, and economy, which suggests that the paper could also be relevant to the sub-field of social informatics (cs.SI).
